         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>yakne</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>kloka</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>ṣṣäṃ</w><w>yok<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>ye</w><w>pā</w><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>i</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>ṣmeṃ</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="2"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>lle</w><pc>•</pc><w>se</w><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>ā</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>śai</w><w>ya</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>lñe</w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment"><hi>pā ·i</hi>: = pā(kr)i?</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣmeṃ</hi>: This syllable occurs mainly in <hi>auṣmeṃ</hi> / <hi>oṃṣmeṃ</hi>, and as a spelling variant in <hi>ṣmeñca</hi>, i.e. often <hi>osta-ṣmeñca</hi> 'householder'. Here it may be possible to read the next akṣara as <hi>c</hi>, so <hi>(osta)-ṣmeṃc(a)</hi> + nts. If correct, this may point to the vinaya.</note><note corresp="#content" type="philcomment">: the only possible key-word is <hi>kloka///</hi>, which could be a form of <hi>klokaśce</hi> ‘pore, follicle’.</note></p>
         </div>
